Absolutely not. But learning to troubleshoot error codes and other behavior is basically the absolute groundfloor for understanding how to code. If you can learn to look up how to do SPECIFIC things successfully -- i.e. how a function works in [your language]; what a for loop is; how to accomplish something specifically in your game engine -- you will be well on your way to a good foundation that you can then build upon with actual coding knowledge. Many, many programmers in the professional space know their way around code, obviously, but a shitload of their time is spent troubleshooting and squashing bugs, which means a lot of research.

>Identify your specific problem
>Ask the right question
>Learn the answer

The original joke was that so many "programmers" just copy code from githubs or stackoverflow posts or something like that
